est Fenollosa, made famous but also distorted by Ezra Pound, the book moves on to the countercultural voices associated with the Beat movement and its friends and heirs such as Ginsberg, Kerouac, Snyder, Giorno, Waldman, and Whalen. The volume also considers the work of contemporary American writers of color influenced by Buddhism, such as Maxine Hong Kingston, Charles Johnson, and Lan Cao. An interview with Kingston is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexBuddhist authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexBuddhist influences. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBuddhism and literaturezUnited States. 0aBuddhism in literature. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : American Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aAugustine, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoon, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHe, Yuemin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingston, Maxine Hong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavazzi, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLutz, R . C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMortenson, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Hanh, 